StringWithMarkup.String: 1-Methoxy-4-methylbenzene's production and use as an synthetic flavor, perfume ingredient, and as a starting material for the preparation of p-anisaldehyde may result in its release to the environment through various waste streams. 1-Methoxy-4-methylbenzene has been detected in lake and effluent water and in blue cheese aroma. If released to soil, 1-methoxy-4-methylbenzene will have low mobility. Volatilization of 1-methoxy-4-methylbenzene may be important from both moist and dry soil surfaces. Insufficient data are available to determine the rate or importance of biodegradation of 1-methoxy-4-methylbenzene in soil or water. If released to water, 1-methoxy-4-methylbenzene may adsorb to suspended solids and sediment. 1-Methoxy-4-methylbenzene may volatilize from water surfaces with estimated half-lives for a model river and model lake of 3.4 hours and 4.4 days, respectively. An estimated BCF value of 62 suggests that 1-methoxy-4-methylbenzene will bioconcentrate only moderately in aquatic organisms. If released to the atmosphere, 1-methoxy-4-methylbenzene will exist in the vapor phase. Vapor-phase 1-methoxy-4-methylbenzene is degraded in the atmosphere by reaction with photochemically produced hydroxyl radicals with an estimated half-life of about 14 hours. 1-Methoxy-4-methylbenzene is released to the atmosphere in emissions from vegetation. The general population may be exposed from contaminated water, application of perfume, and from its presence in food(SRC). Occupational dermal or inhalation exposure may occur during its production and use (SRC)

Section.Description: Sorption to soils and sediments is an important factor on the transport and fate of organic contaminants in the environment.  The soil/water adsorption coefficient, also known as solid-water distribution coefficient (Kd), measures the amount of chemical substance adsorbed onto soil per amount of water.  Since adsorption occurs predominantly by partition into the soil organic matter, it is more useful to normalize the Kd value to the organic carbon content of a soil and express the distribution coefficient in Koc (organic carbon normalized distribution coefficient).  The greater the Kd (or Koc) value, the less likely a chemical will leach or contribute to runoff.  A very high value means it is strongly adsorbed onto soil and organic matter and does not move throughout the soil.
